[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m snapshot_ts = datetime.now(timezone.utc).replace(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     tzinfo=None, microsecond=0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m so `snapshot_ts.isoformat()` produces a naive string like `"2026-05-25T06:34:18"`. `forecast_for_ts` derives from `snapshot_ts + timedelta(...)` which inherits naive-ness:
